u, Muslim, Christian, and Buddhist rituals examine instances of levity that challenge social or religious norms, in which mischievous deities inspire similar behavior among their devotees, and where playful competition incites serious consequences.Sacred Play explores how piety and levity can complement and complicate one another, enriching our understanding of both.Selva J. Raj (1952–2008) was Chair and Stanley S. Kresge Professor of Religious Studies at Albion College. His books include Dealing with Deities: The Ritual Vow in South Asia, also published by SUNY Press, and South Asian Christian Diaspora: Invisible Diaspora in Europe and North America. Corinne G. Dempsey is Associate Professor of Religious Studies at the University of Wisconsin–Stevens Point. She is author of Kerala Christian Sainthood: Collisions of Culture and Worldview in South India and The Goddess Lives in Upstate New York: Breaking Convention and Making Home at a North American Hindu Temple. Together they coedited Popular Christianity in India: Riting between the Lines and Miracle as Modern Conundrum in South Asian Religious Traditions, both also published by SUNY Press.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Anthropology of Religion. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Religion and Philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 4aSociology : Sociology of Religion. 7aRELIGION / Eastern.2bisacsh1 aBard, Amy C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDempsey, Corinne G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDempsey, Corinne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurayappah, Sudharshan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarman, William P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.lo